Hurricane Floyd grew into a Category 5 storm with 250 kph winds and headed toward the Bahamas, threatening the Florida coast of the United States.
Heavy winds and rain pelted the Bahamian capital of Nassau.
Frightened residents in the low-lying archipelago huddled inside their homes and dozens of public shelters as Floyd, with top sustained wind of 150 mph, raked the Bahamas and threatened Florida and Georgia.
As Floyd bore down on the U.S. coast, 2 million people were urged to leave their homes in Florida, Georgia and South Carolina.
President Clinton issued pre-emptive disaster declarations for Florida and Georgia.
